div1.p:
The Carlyles were together most of this last winter and spring, the drama in their lives coming, as always, from their friendship circles and also the rectorial election of TC by the students at the University of Edinburgh. This consisted of two parts, the proposal, acceptance, and election of TC in November 1865, and then the trip to Edinburgh and the giving of the rectorial address to the gathered crowd of students, staff, the University Court, and other invited members of the audience (see 158
          TC to JWC, 3 April 1866
          ), in late March and early April 1866. There was a lot of correspondence in November 1865 between TC and various Edinburgh University connected individuals, David Laing who reluctantly agreed to be TC’s assessor (TC’s representative on the University Court), all the many congratulatory letters from old friends and acquaintances, and TC’s brother, John A. Carlyle, who elected himself advisor to TC while TC used him as the keeper of all the letters generated. TC wrote that he was “perfectly worn out with the shovelfuls of empty Letters … flying abt me all week; one in ten of whh (very unwillingly) I have been compelled to write abt in return” (
  TC to DL, 17 Nov. 1865

). After the election, there was a flurry of correspondence about when TC would give his inaugural address, eventually settled for early April 1866, making traveling easier than a winter event would have allowed for. While JWC toyed with the idea of accompanying TC, she gave short shrift, in a letter to one of her aunts, to the idea that they might move back to Edinburgh to live:

TC extemporized his rectorial address, 2 April, to a large, attentive audience, and Tyndall immediately sent a telegram announcing that it had been “a perfect triumph”; JWC took the telegram to John Forster’s birthday party, 2 April, where she celebrated with Charles Dickens, Forster, and others. This event was only one during an intense period of socializing that JWC took part in while TC was away in Scotland; its intensity later appeared almost to contain a presentiment of her sudden death, but it was simply part of the social pace that JWC adopted over this winter and spring. TC’s letters between October 1865 and March 1866 may be preoccupied with the rectorial events, his own health, and wellbeing, but JWC’s give detailed descriptions of socializing, of a new young friend, of her triumphs over neighbor hens (just like the old days), and of driving out in her carriage. She talked about a particular health problem in letters to Betty Blakiston and to Lady Ashburton, Dec. 1865; it occurred when she was agitated or alarmed: “I was sure to take a pain like a knife-stab at the bottom of my back; that would take my breath away and leave me gasping—like an idiot” (
  JWC to BB, [10 Dec. 1865]
). She apparently discussed it with Geraldine Jewsbury during this last winter, as Jewsbury recalled it in her second letter to Betty Braid after JWC’s death:

div1.q:
When Georgina saw me, I was wild with pain in my arm and hand, and I could not write, with the right hand—could not cut my food, nor sup my soup nor do any one earthly thing with it. After my return from Scotland in August, the pain went away all in a moment, and has never come back!! And tho’ the stiffness remained behind, that also has gradually lessened—till I have recovered such power in my hand that, the other day, I made myself a———Bonnet!! … And I can play on the piano!—and it would be difficult to say what female thing I could not do—if I tried!—(
  JWC to MC, 28 Nov. 1865

)

The nearer we get to the end of March, the more I shudder at a journey of eight hundred miles (there and back) and a Speech for object! I am not so strong as when galloping “Harry” over the Moors! In fact I am now, what is pleasantly called “a Living Miracle!”—That is a woman who ought in the course of Nature to have been dead and buried; but has come alive again; for some purpose;—what? one does not see! (
  JWC to HI, [ca. 3] March 1866

)


I have seen such a curious example lately of the superfluousness of Teachers, where there is capacity to be taught! Some months ago Mr C got a letter from a girl, giving her opinion of himself and his Books—with considerable enthusiasm of—what shall I say?—admiration?—I did not feel sure whether it was admiration or love; but anyhow she expressed herself with an elegance, and eloquence, and real understanding of the subject, that excited my interest in her, and deserved, I thought some answer. So, as Mr C can never be moved to answer unknown adorers, especially unknown female adorers; one day that I had nothing to do, good or bad, I drove to Camberwell to find the “Maria Price” of the Letter. Heavens and Earth! The address she had given was a Tailor’s shop! Not a rich Tailor’s … but a Tailor represented by one waistcoat and one pair of trowsers, in one small window! For one moment my heart failed me, and I was near driving away re infecta. Then I said to myself; is not she the more, not the less worth seeing, for having had no “advantages” in making herself what she is? So I asked if Miss Maria Price was within, and was shown up the smallest stair ever seen, not belonging to a hen roost[.] How there came to me a little creature, looking eleven years old, but in reality six and twenty; how she blushed and flashed into sudden beauty, (like one of Balzac’s colourless Heroines) at Mr Carlyle’s name; How sweetly she looked and spoke, with what modesty and good breeding; how I invited her to Cheyne Row, and how she came, and how Ruskin took her home in his carriage! and how she is turning out the most comfortable protegée that I ever fell into. … I will tell you … when you come. (
  JWC to Lady Am, 7 Nov. 1865

)

div1.p:
JWC’s death was most crushing for TC. But the shock of her sudden death was also palpable in the Carlyles’ social circles. Their friends wrote regretfully to each other as well as to TC, and we have included many of these comments in the footnotes or in the Appendix; the latter includes TC’s journal entry about JWC’s death, Geraldine Jewsbury’s letter to TC, 26 May, describing the events as John Silvester, the coachman, reported them to her, JWC’s obituary in the Haddingtonshire Times, the Times’s description of the funeral, and various letters between friends about the death and TC’s subsequent condition. TC himself, once he had returned to Cheyne Row after JWC’s funeral in Haddington, retreated into silence, writing few letters and receiving hardly any visitors. John A. Carlyle stayed in Cheyne Row with TC: “The Dr seems well & comfortable; is prompt as possible to do any service to me; but there is not now much in his power” (
  TC to JCA, 14 May 1866

). Maggie Welsh, JWC’s cousin, also looked after TC from late April through early August, supervising the household and, initially, sorting JWC’s possessions for disposal. TC wrote to Jean Aitken, mid-May: “Maggie Welsh & he [John A. Carlyle] keep the House from being so ghastly to me, as in its emptiness it wd otherwise be. Maggie is an active orderly polite creature, with a certn truth of sympathy in my sorrow,—and will go at any moment, or stay longer, as I like. Everything is catalogued, and arranged (I believe), in the House; but I have not yet had the heart to take it any way in hand” (
  TC to JCA, 14 May 1866

). This was the background to TC’s own reminiscences of JWC that he began in the notebook of “stories told by herself,” as Geraldine Jewsbury described them (Carlyle, Reminiscences 65), sent to TC, 20 May (MS: NLS 532). TC was stimulated into writing by his disagreement with them. He apparently did not discuss this self-imposed task with John A. Carlyle, as the latter, in a letter to their brother Alick, 4 July, commented on TC’s preoccupation: “He has written as few letters as possible since April, leaving most of them that were absolutely necessary to Miss Welsh and me; but every forenoon he occupies himself some hours with writing that he says nothing of, and reads diligently in the evenings” (Marrs 755). It is in this same letter to Alick that John expressed his somewhat limited appreciation of JWC, indicating that JWC’s dislike of him was returned: “The loss of her of course was a very heavy calamity to him (though none of the rest of us except Mary ever got on well with her); for they were much attached to each other, and she always kept every thing in order most dexterously and faithfully for him, and with all her vehemenius 
[vehemence] of temper was really a most true-hearted and excellent woman” (Marrs 754).

div1.q:
My actual Birth occurred when postage was at a shilling and there-abouts, and it was a natural consequence that people should make their letters long and deliberate, to be worth the money they would cost. Now, one’s letter costs a penny and the penny paid by oneself; and the nicest conscience neednt trouble itself how few lines, and how offhand the lines, that go to a letter on the present terms of postage. Your modern Lady-letter may be written at any moment under any distractions! but as I have said, I was born too far back to adopt this free and easy little-note style—having been early used to filling big square sheets when I wrote at all. Now, I put off and put off always for “some reasonably good leisure” and that being a condition rarely vouchsafed me, with one devilry and another; it happens——as it has happened in your case, that I often give myself the airs of a Brute, without being brutal the least in the world! (
  JWC to MC, 28 Nov. 1865

)

It would be too long to go into details, enough to say, my negociations with “Next door” ended in an agreement that the Cock should be shut up in a cellar inside the owner’s own house—from three in the afternoon till ten in the morning! and in return I give the small boy of the house a lesson every morning in his Reading made Easy!! . … It is a house full of Misteries No 6! I have thoughts of writing a novel about it. (
  JWC to MR, 25 Dec. 1865

)

div1.p:
Thus was laid out the possibility of constructing JWC as a novelist. But this is to distract from her real talents as an exceptional letter writer with a talent for comedy. Her comic timing was often best aimed at TC, so it seems appropriate to end this introduction to her final volume of letters with one of her last jokes at TC’s expense. TC was still in Edinburgh, and Tyndall had called on JWC to tell her about the installation; 
  JWC wrote to TC, [10 April 1866]
: “Alas I missed Tyndalls call! and was ‘vaixed’! He left word with Jessie that you were ‘looking well and every body worshipping you’! and I thought to myself; a pity if he have taken the habit of being worshipped! For he may find some difficulty in keeping it up, here!”

