As for me; I have taken fright at the cold weather, the long journey, and the fuss and agitation of attending my Husband thro’ an operation little more agreeable to him than being hanged!TC noted after JWC’s death that she had mentioned her health in relation to this decision not to subject herself to the stress of attending his rectorial address; JWC told him: “‘I find on any sudden alarm there is a sharp twinge comes into my back, which is like to cut my breath, and seems to stop the heart almost; I should take some fit in the crowded House;—it will never do, really!’ Alas, the doctors now tell me, this meant an affection in some ganglion near the spine; and was a most serious thing, though I did not attach importance to it; but only assented to her practical conclusion as perfectly just” (Carlyle, Reminiscences 188). Geraldine Jewsbury wrote to Betty Braid, 23 April, after JWC’s death: “Mrs Carlyle always when she was alarmed or agitated had a great sudden pain in her Back wh took her breath for the moment she used to say her mother had it & that some day it would kill her” (see Appendix 260 GEJ to KST, 29 April 1866
