). He was introduced to TC, whom he had long admired, by Emerson, 1848; helped TC as an unpaid sec., translated his work into German, and twice accompanied him on visits to Germany (1852 and 1858). From 1856–63 Neuberg lived at Oakley Villas, 25 (renumbered 140) Adelaide Rd., with his widowed sister, Rosetta (or Rosette) (ca. 1816–98)—who had m., ca. 1851, Adolph Frankau (1820–56; see 
  32:32
  TC to JAC, 19 Nov. 1856

)—and her two children, Frederick Joseph (b. 1854 and Gertrude Rosette Adolphine (b. ca. 1856). In 1863 they moved to Roslyn Park, Hampstead. After Frankau’s death, Neuberg managed Frankau’s company, which imported meerschaum pipes and fancy goods, at 25 Clements Lane, Lombard St., London.

Spedding, Thomas Story (1800–70; see 10:32 TC to TSS, 17 Feb. 1838
), m., 1839, Frances Elizabeth (previously called Emily in error), b. Headlam (1811–96); their children
were Margaret Emily (1842–73), Frances Ellen (1843–1900), Maria Isabella (d. in infancy 1845), Henry Anthony (1846–87), and Mildred Eyre (1848–1918). They lived at Mirehouse, nr. Keswick, Cumberland. A lawyer, he devoted his life to local interests in Cumberland. He and his brother James Spedding (1808–81; ODNB; see 8:196 JWC to JCA, [Mid-August 1835] , and 19:205 TC to TSS, 20 Sept. 1845
), literary editor and biographer, had been friends of TC’s since the late 1830s. James lived in Westbourne Grove, London.

Welsh, John (1785–1853; see 28:286–87 TC to JCA, [12 Oct. 1853] ), JWC’s maternal uncle, brass and copper founder, who had lived at 20 Maryland St., Liverpool; m., 1808, Mary, b. Colliver (d. 1838; see 10:200 TC to AC, 15 Oct. 1838
); their children were Helen (ca. 1813–53); Walter; Alexander; Jeannie (Babbie) (1818–95), m., 1853,
Andrew Chrystal (ca. 1811–83), wine merchant from Glasgow, they had a da., Mary (1857–1937), see 40:226–27 40:biographical notes ; John (1820–60); Margaret; and Mary.

Welsh, John Amelia (“Jackie”) (ca. 1812–64), illegitimate da. of JWC’s paternal uncle William (1790–1819; see 
  14:90TC to JWC, 25 March 1842
), had lived in Haddington with her mother, Elizabeth Scott (b. 1782, presumably now dead), and her aunt Jane Scott (1787–1863).

Welsh, Robert (1786–1841; see 13:118 TC to JWC, 29 April 1841
, and 14:217 JWC to MW, [8 July? 1842] ), JWC’s paternal uncle, Edinburgh solicitor; m., 1821, Mary, b. May (b. 1796). Their children were John May (1824–56; see 19:98–99 JWC to MR, 12 July [1845]
); Sarah (b. 1825; d. before 1832); Elizabeth (1828–38?); Mary May (1829–85), m., 1859, as his second wife, Dr. Robert Martin Craven (1824–1903; see 35:267 35:biographical notes ); Sarah (1832–56); Robert (1833—Spring 1866); Annabella (1834–55); and Grace (1836–63), m., 1859, William Henry Dobie (b. ca. 1809).
